How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travels only to the socialist block, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went from vacation to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime turned to the west and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) would not be allowed to travel freely and individually by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at that time, but one should put on the tail with a sleeping bag and spend the night like this, or have "known goods" in the agency.
Still not everything was earned.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically untrustworthy people", which could not travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses that the Czechs would acquire.
The way of travelling from the Czechs has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was no longer the holiday in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, from which we are no longer aware today, that Croatia could not travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia since then.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to the neighbouring Western European States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see the maps of the trips to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups slept in the parks in campaign shops, as our income from that time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was taking food (conservations, embittered, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with him also the average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increased demand for travel, the agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to prepare travel using charter flights, which led to an incredibly low prices for travel compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volumes.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs had already traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Chequia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been making distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Chequia to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, with what our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head in foreign travel, including spending on the site of stay.
