The North Stream, new entrance door of Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia passing through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must provide gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with a great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic coasts, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned together the valve wheel that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, it will reach 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe each year through a first 1224 km pipeline that communicate the San Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, the possibility of constructing a third tube is already discussed on the same route.
For Gazprom, the time-concluding of this huge work presents the air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow direct supply of gas to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
These two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, whether the topic is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has only known for five years to triumph over its vision of a direct partnership between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us," said François Fillon during the launch of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel covered with concrete to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is located at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not broken all over its length: not by valves, not by maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged in Sweden's waters, but the project's managers gave up the project to see that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently at sea in front of their backs.
"In case we have, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a flight will take place, since it has been envisaged that, according to the forecasts, they will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a submarine robot, drawn by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device running through the interior of the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it enters the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three metres per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any type of repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed by pressure only.
At first it's 200 bars and 100 bars.
Five companies have joined their forces to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
To her, Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a common company, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented this company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, the total capacity of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7,400 million for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of spending on its own.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Some valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas at arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
The total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
